ach other out while keeping their individual senses of self. Focusing on representative works of literature, film, and philosophy, the contributors identify the problems vexing these countries (war, economic competition) as well as possible solutions (the Maastricht treaty, increasing youth exchange). From the literary salons of the eighteenth century to the trenches of the twentieth, from a love-hate relationship to one of cooperation and peace, this book investigates the unique and volatile dialectic between these two nations and cultures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aArea Studies : French Studies. 4aCultural Studies : German Culture. 4aHistory : History. 4aLiterature : Comparative Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh1 aBrueggemann, Aminia M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrueggemann, Aminia M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCloonan, William J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Sande, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForrest, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGogröf-Voorhees, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon, Terri J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuenther, Beatrice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHealey, Kimberley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeaman, Elliot, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPayne, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSasson, Sarah Juliette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchlipphacke, Heidi M., econt